  "prompt": "Is white an actual color?",
  "response": "Yes, white is considered an actual color in the context of art, design, and everyday perception. It is often described as the presence of all colors of light combined, as it reflects and scatters all visible wavelengths of light to the human eye, resulting in what we perceive as white. In color theory, especially in the RGB (red, green, blue) color model used for digital screens, white is created by combining all three primary colors at their full intensity.\n\nIn contrast, in pigment-based color models like CMYK (cyan, magenta, yellow, and key/black) used in printing, white is typically the absence of color or pigment on a surface and is often the natural color of the paper or substrate.\n\nSo, white is both a color and a concept used differently depending on whether you're dealing with light or pigments.",
